  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "834c1b4d-0f47-468e-a6d8-c0e886db1eb2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As can be seen, some models do not perform very. One should take into account, however, that no hyperparameter has been tuned for any of the models in this example. Class imbalance also seems to play an important role since many examples from class 5 (the smallest class) are wrongly predicted as belonging to any of the other classes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "af9331e7-44c4-49c7-bf66-865dfa6646e5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Task for you 1\n",
    "\n",
    "Undersample the not-5 class (False) by randomly choosing examples to define a balanced training dataset and compare the performance with what has been presented here. Examples discarded from the training dataset to prevent imbalance can be used for testing."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "35922bd6-134f-4add-b2e2-a1aa3443a625",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Cross-validation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "261cb754-90c6-4311-b127-d3aae46bcced",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Sometimes the machine learning algorithms fit very well the training dataset but are not able to generalise well to predict unseen examples (i.e. the test dataset). This is typically referred as overfitting.\n",
    "\n",
    "Cross-validation (CV) is a method used to minimise overfitting.\n",
    "\n",
    "The idea is to split the training dataset into two sets: one used for training and the other for validation (the test data is not used until the end). \n",
    "\n",
    "Basid approach (**k-fold CV**): The training set is split into $k$ smaller sets and we proceed as follows for each of the k “folds”:\n",
    "* A model is trained using $k-1$ of the folds as training data;\n",
    "* the resulting model is validated on the remaining part of the data (i.e., it is used as a test set to compute a performance measure such as accuracy).\n",
    "\n",
    "The performance measure reported by $k$-fold cross-validation is then the average of the values computed in the loop.\n",
    "\n",
    "<div>\n",
    "<img src=\"grid_search_cross_validation2.png\" width=\"500\"/>\n",
    "</div>\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "edcbb249-5395-4921-842c-2a045673d4f7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Cross-validation with a random forest classifier"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "68f51b2b-76bc-458a-a53a-2994e3f63025",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us use cross-validation for a random forest classifier which gave a large number of false positive for the False class (not-5 or 0). This is presumably due to class imbalance despite the fact that random forests are often presented as a good method to automatically correct for class imbalance (hypertuning might have also affected the perfomance)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 39,
   "id": "32467759-3e2a-4bbb-9bb3-cdb7d8dddee1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 39,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier\n",
    "rfc = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)\n",
    "rfc.fit(X_train, y_train_5)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 40,
   "id": "f7dd8c92-4d01-429f-ae2e-e2037a697abc",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "y_pred_test = rfc.predict(X_test)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 42,
   "id": "869d39bc-3623-4a96-9d5d-1bc5b5c0d0cc",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "array([0.98885, 0.9863 , 0.98635])"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 42,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score\n",
    "cross_val_score(rfc, X_train, y_train_5, cv=3, scoring=\"accuracy\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "34c584f4-9316-4650-84c2-c4fbcecb7994",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To compute the confusion matrix, you first need to have a set of predictions, so they\n",
    "can be compared to the actual targets. You could make predictions on the test set, but\n",
    "let’s keep it untouched for now (remember that you want to use the test set only at the\n",
    "very end of your project, once you have a classifier that you are ready to launch).\n",
    "Instead, you can use the cross_val_predict() function:\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 43,
   "id": "ad3bbf25-746e-4813-90b0-6feed5dc7024",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_predict\n",
    "y_train_pred = cross_val_predict(rfc, X_train, y_train_5, cv=3)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8a1d5fca-986d-479a-a804-f9f8d5a7496f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Just like the cross_val_score() function, cross_val_predict() performs K-fold\n",
    "cross-validation, but instead of returning the evaluation scores, it returns the predictions made on each test fold. This means that you get a clean prediction for each\n",
    "instance in the training set (“clean” meaning that the prediction is made by a model\n",
    "that never saw the data during training)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 59,
   "id": "7914c989-98e6-4cb6-bf5c-c91a633c16a4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "array([[54534,    45],\n",
       "       [  725,  4696]], dtype=int64)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 59,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix\n",
    "confusion_matrix(y_train_5, y_train_pred)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5ed4f586-5973-40a9-bede-2734652d313a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Note that crossvalidation reduced the false positive rate for the largest class."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0d8c77d9-2df3-41a6-9b86-c24c26e96a31",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Hyperparameter tuning with crossvalidation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "02530ebd-a42d-4ea6-8b56-0c3971c12c5a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**GridSearchCV** is an Sklearn function for model selection. \n",
    "\n",
    "It does an exhaustive search over a set of parameters. \n",
    "\n",
    "The parameter `cv` of the function is the number of cross-validation splits (default value cv = 5)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "93ad4a5c-4a8a-4807-8f45-c533cb0f2b37",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### KNN model\n",
    "\n",
    "To start with, I consider the hyperparameter tuning of the KNN model:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 48,
   "id": "24afbbd7-0e52-44cc-b134-e8ea885d606b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV\n",
    "\n",
    "# I will use more than one parallel processors to run this. It should be faster\n",
    "knn2 = KNeighborsClassifier(n_jobs=2) \n",
    "\n",
    "param_grid = {\n",
    "    'n_neighbors': [5*i for i in range(1,9)]\n",
    "}"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 49,
   "id": "73e584df-e406-471b-87ed-7caa8a528f6a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "GridSearchCV(cv=5, estimator=KNeighborsClassifier(n_jobs=2),\n",
       "             param_grid={'n_neighbors': [5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40]})"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 49,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Warning: This can take long\n",
    "CV_knn2 = GridSearchCV(estimator=knn2, param_grid=param_grid, cv= 5)\n",
    "CV_knn2.fit(X_train, y_train_5)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 50,
   "id": "4eebffb5-6341-41b2-b6e6-729f7bd2b526",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "{'n_neighbors': 5}"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 50,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "CV_knn2.best_params_"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 51,
   "id": "d5dbc164-a357-4e61-92ce-ab86f1416e0f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "knn3 = KNeighborsClassifier(n_jobs=2, n_neighbors = 5)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 52,
   "id": "7ae92cc9-62ff-4efe-b4ec-5184d2c5e19d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "array([[9085,   23],\n",
       "       [  38,  854]], dtype=int64)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 52,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "knn3.fit(X_train, y_train_5)\n",
    "y_pred_test_knn3 = knn3.predict(X_test)\n",
    "confusion_matrix(y_test_5, y_pred_test_knn3)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 61,
   "id": "80831bc3-37f2-42b5-a6a7-e6ea812c5336",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "Text(33.0, 0.5, 'True class')"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 61,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "s = sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix(y_test_5, y_pred_test_knn3),annot=True, fmt=\".0f\")\n",
    "s.set_xlabel('Predicted class', fontsize=10)\n",
    "s.set_ylabel('True class', fontsize=10)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a7d28a07-820b-42a9-b5a6-ca2cc7b3dce9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For this particular dataset, the KNN did mostly equally well without cross-validation. However, hyperparameter tuning with cross-validation is good in general to ensure that our classifiers are optimised."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8ad4a174-17b8-42e0-a7af-a1c555c68455",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Task for you 2\n",
    "The random forest model has more parameters that can be tuned. Use hyperparameter tuning with crossvalidation with the following parameter ranges: 'n_estimators': [200, 500], 'max_depth': [4,5,6,7,8], 'criterion':['gini', 'entropy']."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "497c2e5d-6951-491d-9fae-253f4a9d45fe",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Does the Mathematica superfunction `Classify` use cross-validation automatically?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "59ce4da2-adbc-4a85-882f-bcdc8d9199ce",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "No.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Mathematica automated function `Classify` uses a more advanced strategy than the simple cross-validation described above. Two stages are involved:\n",
    "* First, it tries many combinations of models (e.g. random forest, KNN, etc.) and hyperparameters on small training sets.\n",
    "* Second, it only trains the most promising configurations on larger training sets and selects the one that gives the best performance.\n",
    "\n",
    "You can try this with Mathematica, as in the figure. Each curve in 'the learning curves for all the algorithms' plot corresponds to a different method and set of hyperparameters. As can be seen, only some combinations are trained on the full training set. \n",
    "\n",
    "The strategy followed by the `Classify` function falls within the category of [Automated Machine Learning](https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-3-030-05318-5).\n",
    "\n",
    "<div>\n",
    "<img src=\"Mathematica_Classifier_LearningCurves.png\" width=\"500\"/>\n",
    "</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6cfa5745-6fa1-4f50-a7b9-0b309d2783ba",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Multiclass classification"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ab9927ad-3b2b-4b1d-9f7c-69655a179ce5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Multiclass classifiers (also called multinomial classifiers) can distinguish between more than two classes.\n",
    "\n",
    "For example, one may want to classify the MNIST images into 10 classes. This can be done with two different strategies:\n",
    "\n",
    "* One-versus-all (OvA): Train as many classifiers as classes, i.e. one classifier for each class. For the MNIST dataset, this means a classifier for 0, a classifier for 1, etc.\n",
    "\n",
    "* One-versus-one (OvO): A classifier for every pair of classes (i.e. one to distinguish 0s and 1s, another to distinguish 0s and 2s, another for 1s and 2s, and so on).\n",
    "\n",
    "Sklearn automatically detects when the labels list contains more than two classes and uses OvA for most machine learning algorithms."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 54,
   "id": "f0ea5731-dcce-47c6-b5ad-ae4cf1b75e31",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "KNeighborsClassifier()"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 54,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier\n",
    "knn_clf_Multi = KNeighborsClassifier()\n",
    "knn_clf_Multi.fit(X_train, y_train)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 55,
   "id": "3a474bd2-4a8b-4ba6-bdb4-de2843dd817b",
   "metadata": {},
